{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524731"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:07:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:07:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14024"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14024"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.08,0.78,0.11,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6673"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49741"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6673"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14024"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34995"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1170"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"9636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11224"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13780"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43464"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49741"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of nausea, vomiting, and diarrhoea. She reports passing watery stools up to eight times per day and has been unable to keep fluids down. She has a medical history of obesity, hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her medications include amlodipine 10mg daily and Panadol Osteo (main ingredient paracetamol) 1330mg three times a day. She occassionally takes one-two tablets of ibuprofen 200mg per week for exacerbations of her osteoarthritis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Her mucous membranes are dry, and she has reduced skin turgor. Abdominal examination reveals mild generalised tenderness without guarding or organomegaly. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPathology test results reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT: 45 U/L (5 - 35)\u003Cbr /\u003ESodium: 134 mmol/L (135-145)\u003Cbr /\u003EPotassium: 5.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EUrea: 18 mmol/L (2.5-6.7)\u003Cbr /\u003ECreatinine: 180 \u03bcmol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT scan of the kidneys, ureters and bladder (KUB) identified no renal calculi or hydronephrosis. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s acute kidney injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Contrast-induced nephropathy","HRS-AKI (type 1 hepatorenal syndrome)","Hypovolaemia","Acute interstitial nephritis","Urinary tract obstruction"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs consistent with hypovolaemia due to gastrointestinal losses, which has led to acute kidney injury (AKI). \u003Cstrong\u003EHypovolaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause of her AKI given her history of vomiting and diarrhoea, clinical signs of dehydration (tachycardia, hypotension, dry mucous membranes, reduced skin turgor), and laboratory findings consistent with pre-renal AKI (elevated urea and creatinine).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContrast-induced nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs 24-72 hours after administration of iodinated contrast media. There is no history of recent contrast administration in this case (CT KUB is traditionally a non-contrast scan), making this an unlikely cause of her AKI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHRS-AKI (type 1 hepatorenal syndrome)\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition whereby portal hypertension leads to splanchnic vasodilation, leading to reduced effective circulatory volume and subsequently activation of the RAAS (renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system), resulting in AKI via renal vasoconstriction. The stem does not stipulate a history of liver cirrhosis or other causes of portal hypertension, and the mild transaminitis might be explained by the paracetamol use in an unwell patient and/or a chronic rise from possible metabolic associated fatty liver disease (MAFLD) secondary to the patient\u0027s obesity. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary tract obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a post-renal AKI however is excluded by the CT KUB findings. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESuch relatively minimal use of non-steroidal anti-inflammatory agents (NSAIDs) would be unlikely to cause \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute interstitial nephritis, \u003C/strong\u003Eand the clinical scenario of excess GI losses resulting in hypovolaemia provides a clearer explanation for the patient\u0027s acute kidney injury. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypovolaemia is a common cause of acute kidney injury, particularly in the context of gastrointestinal losses.","Assessment of volume status is crucial in patients presenting with acute kidney injury.","Careful history-taking and physical examination are essential in determining the underlying cause of acute kidney injury."],"references":["Goyal A, Daneshpajouhnejad P, Hashmi MF, Bashir K. Acute kidney injury (acute renal failure) [Internet]. PubMed. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441896/","Ranasinghe IR, Sharma B, Bashir K. Hepatorenal Syndrome [Internet]. PubMed. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430856/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34995"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14024"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34995"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-03T15:48:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-03T15:51:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6673"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49741"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{